        <div class="section-label text-accent-bright/80 mb-6">Food Conveyors</div>
        <h1 class="font-display text-5xl sm:text-6xl lg:text-7xl font-extrabold text-white tracking-wide uppercase leading-[0.95] mb-8">
          Cooling <span class="text-accent-bright">Conveyors</span>
        </h1>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <article>
    <section class="py-12 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="aio-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <p id="aio-heading" class="text-lg text-ink leading-relaxed">
          A cooling conveyor transports hot or warm products through a cooling zone to reduce temperature before packaging, coating, or further processing. Cooling methods include ambient (natural convection), forced-air (fan-driven airflow across the belt), refrigerated tunnel (chilled air at 33-40 F), and cryogenic (liquid nitrogen or CO2 spray). Spiral cooling conveyors compact 200+ feet of cooling length into a vertical tower occupying 100-150 square feet of floor space. Manufacturers like Ashworth, Intralox, Wire Belt Company, and Linde (cryogenic) supply cooling conveyor belt systems and complete cooling solutions.
        </p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ WHY COOLING MATTERS ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="why-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Fundamentals</div>
        <h2 id="why-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Why Cooling Before <span class="text-accent">Packaging Matters</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Packaging warm product traps moisture inside the package. Trapped moisture condenses on the inside of the film as the product cools, creating visible fog (consumer complaint) and a moist environment that promotes mold growth (food safety hazard and reduced shelf life). Each product has a target packaging temperature , exceed it, and you get quality and safety problems.
          </p>
          <p>
            Target packaging temperatures vary by product:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Bread:</strong> 95-100 F (35-38 C) , below the dew point inside the bag to prevent condensation</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Cookies and crackers:</strong> 80-90 F (27-32 C) , prevents soft texture and moisture migration in sealed packages</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Confectionery (chocolate):</strong> 60-65 F (16-18 C) , prevents bloom and ensures proper snap</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Cooked meat:</strong> Below 40 F (4 C) , food safety requirement per USDA cooling guidelines</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Industrial parts:</strong> Varies by downstream process , coating, assembly, or inspection temperature requirements</li>
          </ul>
          <!-- VERIFY: USDA cooked meat cooling requirements and temperature targets -->
          <p>
            The cooling conveyor bridges the gap between the process (oven, fryer, cooker, molder) and the packaging line. Insufficient cooling time or capacity becomes a production bottleneck , the cooling conveyor sets the maximum line speed when it is the limiting factor.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ COOLING METHODS ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="methods-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Cooling Methods</div>
        <h2 id="methods-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Ambient, Forced-Air & <span class="text-accent">Refrigerated Cooling</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-4 mb-4">Ambient Cooling</h3>
          <p>
            Ambient cooling relies on natural convection , room-temperature air passively removes heat from the product surface. No fans, no refrigeration, no energy cost beyond the conveyor drive. Ambient cooling works for products with low thermal mass (thin cookies, crackers, flatbreads) and long available cooling time. The limiting factor is the product's surface-to-volume ratio , thin products cool quickly by convection; thick, dense products cool slowly.
          </p>
          <p>
            Ambient cooling conveyors use open mesh belts that allow air circulation from below. Belt speed is slow , 3 to 10 FPM , to maximize residence time. For <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/bakery/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">bakery applications</a>, ambient spirals preserve crust moisture on bread better than forced-air systems.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-10 mb-4">Forced-Air Cooling</h3>
          <p>
            Forced-air cooling uses fans or blowers to push conditioned air across the product on the belt. Air velocity across the product surface increases the convective heat transfer coefficient by 2-5x compared to ambient, reducing required cooling time (and conveyor length) proportionally. Air can be room temperature, conditioned (dehumidified), or chilled.
          </p>
          <p>
            Forced-air cooling tunnels enclose the conveyor in an insulated housing with air handling units. Air enters through distribution plenums, flows across the belt tiers (cross-flow or counter-flow pattern), and exits through return ducts. Cross-flow directs air perpendicular to product travel. Counter-flow blows air against the direction of travel, exposing the coolest product to the coldest air for maximum temperature differential.
          </p>
          <p>
            Cookie and cracker lines use forced-air cooling to accelerate cooling and free floor space. However, excessive air velocity dries the product surface , bakeries balance airflow rate against moisture loss. Adjustable fan speed (via VFD) lets operators tune airflow for different products.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-10 mb-4">Refrigerated Cooling</h3>
          <p>
            Refrigerated cooling tunnels use mechanical refrigeration (compressor-driven) to cool air to 33-40 F before it contacts the product. Required for products needing temperatures below ambient , chocolate confections, cooked meats, cheese, and temperature-sensitive pharmaceuticals. Refrigerated tunnels cost significantly more to purchase and operate than ambient or forced-air systems due to the refrigeration plant, insulated enclosure, and energy consumption.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-10 mb-4">Cryogenic Cooling</h3>
          <p>
            Cryogenic cooling sprays liquid nitrogen (LN2) or liquid carbon dioxide (CO2) directly onto product on the conveyor belt. Surface temperatures drop to -100 F or below within seconds. Cryogenic cooling suits products requiring rapid crust-freezing (IQF shrimp, berries, meat patties), chocolate enrobing (rapid set), and applications where floor space for conventional cooling is unavailable. Linde, Air Liquide, and Messer supply cryogenic cooling tunnels with integrated conveyor systems. <!-- VERIFY: Current cryogenic tunnel manufacturers and product names -->
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ SPIRAL COOLERS ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="spiral-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Spiral Systems</div>
        <h2 id="spiral-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Spiral <span class="text-accent">Cooling Conveyors</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Spiral coolers stack a continuous belt in a helical path inside a tower. Product rides the belt upward or downward through multiple tiers. A 10-foot-diameter, 15-foot-tall spiral provides 300+ feet of effective belt length in a 100-square-foot floor footprint , a 10:1 floor space advantage over straight-line coolers.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Self-Stacking vs. Drum-Driven Spirals</h3>
          <p>
            Two spiral belt technologies dominate the market:
          </p>
          <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-3 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Self-stacking (overdrive):</strong> The belt layers stack on top of each other, supported by the belt's own structure (collapsing links or overlay bars). No intermediate support structure inside the spiral. Self-stacking belts handle heavier loads and more tiers. Ashworth and Intralox manufacture self-stacking spiral belt systems.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Drum-driven:</strong> A central rotating drum drives the belt through friction. The drum supports the belt from the inside. Drum-driven spirals provide smoother, more consistent belt tension and gentler product handling. Preferred for fragile products like decorated cakes, open-top cups, and unstable containers.</li>
          </ul>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Spiral Cooler Sizing</h3>
          <p>
            Spiral cooler size depends on four factors: required cooling time, belt width, belt speed, and product loading density. A wider belt handles more product per tier. More tiers (taller tower) provide longer cooling time. Belt speed determines throughput , faster speeds mean shorter residence time per product but higher products-per-minute capacity.
          </p>
          <p>
            Typical spiral cooler specifications for bakery applications: 24 to 48 inch belt width, 10 to 30 tiers, 8 to 15 foot tower diameter, and 2 to 8 FPM belt speed. For a complete overview of <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/bakery/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">bakery conveyor systems</a>, see our dedicated guide.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ MESH BELT TYPES ═══ -->
