                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">20-40%</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">-40 to 1200 F</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Heavy products, flat surface</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Honeycomb</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">40-60%</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">-40 to 900 F</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Max airflow, light products</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$</td>
              </tr>
              <tr class="border-b border-border">
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Modular plastic (perforated)</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">15-30%</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">-40 to 250 F</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Low-temp cooling, easy cleaning</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$-$$$</td>
              </tr>
              <tr>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-semibold text-ink">Spiral (self-stacking)</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">25-45%</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4 font-mono text-sm">-40 to 500 F</td>
                <td class="py-4 pr-4">Spiral towers, compact cooling</td>
                <td class="py-4 font-mono text-sm">$$$-$$$$</td>
              </tr>
            </tbody>
          </table>
        </div>
        <!-- VERIFY: Belt open area percentages and temperature ratings per manufacturer specs -->
        <p class="text-sm text-ink-muted mt-4">Open area and temperature specifications vary by manufacturer and wire gauge. Contact belt manufacturers for application-specific recommendations.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ APPLICATIONS ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface" aria-labelledby="apps-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Applications</div>
        <h2 id="apps-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Cooling Conveyor <span class="text-accent">Applications</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-4 mb-4">Bakery</h3>
          <p>
            <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/bakery/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Bakery cooling</a> is the largest application for cooling conveyors. Bread exits the oven at 200+ F and must cool to 95-100 F before slicing and bagging. Cookies cool from 300 F to 80-90 F before wrapping. <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/bakery/cookie-cracker/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">Cookie and cracker lines</a> need gentle handling during cooling to prevent breakage.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Confectionery</h3>
          <p>
            Chocolate-enrobed products (bars, nuts, pretzels) pass through a cooling tunnel to set the chocolate coating. The tunnel maintains 55-65 F with controlled humidity to prevent bloom (white discoloration from fat or sugar crystal migration). Belt speed and tunnel length provide 5-15 minutes of cooling time. Cooling tunnels for confectionery use stainless steel mesh belts and <a href="/industries/food-conveyors/sanitary/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">sanitary frame construction</a>.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Meat and Poultry</h3>
          <p>
            Cooked meat products must cool from cooking temperature (165+ F) to below 40 F within USDA-mandated time limits to prevent bacterial growth. Spiral coolers with refrigerated air handling achieve rapid cooling in a compact footprint. Stainless steel construction and IP69K-rated components handle the daily washdown required in meat plants.
          </p>

          <h3 class="font-display text-2xl font-bold uppercase tracking-wider text-ink mt-8 mb-4">Industrial and Non-Food</h3>
          <p>
            Cooling conveyors serve non-food applications including plastic part cooling after injection molding, metal part cooling after heat treatment, rubber product cooling after vulcanization, and glass cooling after forming. These applications use carbon steel mesh belts (no food-grade requirement) and ambient or forced-air cooling. Part weight and temperature determine belt construction and support structure.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- ═══ SIZING ═══ -->
    <section class="py-20 bg-surface-dim" aria-labelledby="sizing-heading">
      <div class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8">
        <div class="section-label text-accent mb-4">Engineering</div>
        <h2 id="sizing-heading" class="font-display text-4xl sm:text-5xl font-extrabold text-ink tracking-wide uppercase mb-8">
          Sizing a <span class="text-accent">Cooling Conveyor</span>
        </h2>
        <div class="text-lg text-ink-muted leading-relaxed space-y-5">
          <p>
            Cooling conveyor sizing starts with required cooling time , the time needed to reduce product from inlet temperature to target temperature. Cooling time depends on product thermal properties (mass, specific heat, thermal conductivity, surface area), cooling medium temperature, and air velocity.
          </p>
          <p>
            A simplified sizing approach:
          </p>
          <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-3 ml-2">
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Determine required cooling time</strong> from product testing or heat transfer calculations. For bakery products, empirical data from similar products is the most reliable source.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Calculate belt length</strong> = belt speed (FPM) x cooling time (minutes). For spirals, this is the total belt path length inside the tower.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Determine belt width</strong> from product width, number of lanes, and edge clearance. Minimum 2 inches of edge clearance per side.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Calculate throughput</strong> = products per belt foot x belt speed (FPM). Verify that throughput meets production requirements.</li>
            <li><strong class="text-ink">Add 15-20% safety factor</strong> for product variation, ambient temperature changes, and belt loading inefficiency.</li>
          </ol>
          <p>
            For budgeting, straight-line ambient cooling conveyors cost $$ per linear foot. Forced-air tunnels cost $$$ due to the enclosure, air handling, and controls. Spiral coolers cost $$$$ but deliver maximum cooling capacity per square foot of floor space. See the <a href="/resources/conveyor-cost-guide/" class="text-accent hover:text-accent-hover font-semibold">conveyor cost guide</a> for detailed cost factors.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

